data.content:
Your code **does not use `Thread.Abort`**, `Thread.Interrupt`, or catch `ThreadAbortException`. It only uses `Thread.Start()`, `Thread.Join()`, and `Thread.Sleep()` — all of which work identically in .NET 8 with no migration needed.

**No Thread.Abort migration is required here.**

That said, for modern .NET 8, you'd benefit from replacing raw threads with `Task.WhenAll` + `CancellationToken` for better resource usage:

```csharp
public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));
    await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
}

private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    Thread.Sleep(100); // or await Task.Delay(100, ct)
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
}
```

This gives you cooperative cancellation (the modern replacement for `Thread.Abort`) if you ever need to stop work mid-flight.
